		<body>
			<pb n="1"/>
			<p rend="indent(1)"><addressee>Rev. Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
				<p>Dear Sir&#33;</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">I thank you for a copy of your Bible.  It<lb/> is indeed a handsome edition.  I am sorry that it came too<lb/> late to be noticed by me in the Introduction<lb/> p. XV&#44; which was printed before your Bible came to my<lb/> hands.  Still I shall notice it in its proper place.</p>
				<p><persName>Dr. Huerst</persName> of <placeName>Leipzig</placeName> has &#40;in his Bibliotheca Judaica&#41;<lb/> betrayed a profound ignorance of American literature.</p>
				<p>So he wrote</p>
				<p><persName>Isaac Leeser</persName> &#40;Pr. in <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>&#41;&#59; The Occident &#40;Eine<lb/> Monatsschrift f&#252;r j&#252;d. Intressen&#41;.  III. Jahrg&#228;nge.<lb/> <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName> <date>1843&#45;46</date>.8.</p>
				<p>He not only forgot to mention your own books&#44; but<lb/> also those which you edited.  I called his attention to<lb/> this and other facts&#44; and he desired me to give him<lb/> correct statements in regard to <placeName>America</placeName>.  Please<lb/> send me a list of your own books and those<lb/> edited by you&#44; together with the necessary dates.</p>
				<p>I believe my friend <persName>Kalisch</persName> is with you in <placeName>Ph.</placeName>  I pray<lb/> you to encourage him&#59; he is too much of an <add>Hebrew</add> and<lb/> needs cheering up&#44; if we are to expect something great of<lb/> him.</p>
				<p>I send you the first volume of my history by mail<lb/> because this is the cheapest way.  If you should think<lb/> it worth while to <sic>criticise</sic> it&#44; I will call your attention<lb/> to the passages in it which are new&#44; and therefore<lb/> exposed to criticism.</p>
				<p>1. The distinction between history and religion.  Introd. XV.</p>
				<p>2. The death of <persName>Jacob</persName> p 35. 36.</p>
				<p>3. The title of the Israelites to the land of <placeName>Canaan</placeName> p 37 to 40. 110.</p>
				<p>4. Identity of the Anakims with Manetha&#39;s Hyksas<add>&#63;</add>&#44; who<lb/> were the oppressors of <placeName>Israel</placeName> in <placeName>Egypt</placeName> p. 41&#45;54</p>
				<p>5. Exposition of the Decalogue p. 80&#45;84</p>
				<p>6. The <sic>defence</sic> of <persName>Joshua</persName> <sic>p</sic> 213&#45;216</p>
			<pb n="2"/>
				<p>7. Chronological position of the administration<lb/> of <persName>Samson</persName> and <persName>Jephtah</persName> p. 234. 265 to 269.&#44; which<lb/> makes new the whole period of Judges.</p>
				<p>8. The <sic>highschool</sic> at <placeName>Ramah</placeName> 250&#45;256.</p>
				<p>9. Chronological investigation on <persName>David&#39;s</persName> seven<lb/> years in <placeName>Hebron</placeName>324</p>
				<p>10. Reconciliation of <persName>I. Samuel</persName> 16.17. 18308</p>
				<p>11. The wars of <persName>David</persName>337&#45;344</p>
				<p>12. The revolt under and after <persName>Solomon</persName>377&#45;384</p>
				<p>Almost the whole history of the Kings is new&#44; having<lb/> <sic>reconciliated</sic> <persName>Samuel</persName>&#44;  Kings&#44; and Chronicles&#44; and<lb/> having compared scriptural passages with the<lb/> late discoveries in <placeName>Nineveh</placeName> xc.</p>
				<p>The four appendices are totally new.  I have established<lb/> that <persName>moses</persName> wrote the Pentateuch&#44; that this law and<lb/> religion was the code of the nation in all ages&#44; which<lb/> was most emphatically negatived by modern critics&#59; that<lb/> the historical books were written much earlier than<lb/> <persName>Jost</persName> and others believed&#59; that art and science flourished<lb/> among the ancient Israelites&#59; and that they were thoroughly<lb/> democratic and invincible patriots.  In religion I have<lb/> not only rushed many a hypercritical assertion&#59; but<lb/> also the grand supposition&#44; that the prophets did not<lb/> understand Judaism until <persName>Jesus</persName> came to expound it.<lb/>  The faults you will find&#44; and I am ready to hear<lb/> them.</p>
			<p rend="indent(2)">Most Respectfully</p>
			<p rend="indent(3)">Yours</p>
			<p rend="indent(2)"><persName role="author">Isaac M. Wise</persName></p>
			<p rend="indent(1)"><placeName>Albany</placeName> <date>December 7. 5614</date></p>
			<p rend="indent(4)"><date>1854</date></p>
